  <p>Before spending money on courses or tutors, take stock of where you are right now. If you cannot read pinyin confidently, that is your starting point regardless of any other goals. If you can hold a basic conversation but struggle with reading menus or street signs, your priority should be character recognition. A common trap is choosing resources based on marketing rather than on honest self-assessment. Write down three specific weaknesses — for example, "I confuse second and third tones," "I cannot read more than 200 characters," or "I freeze when someone speaks to me at normal speed." Then select tools that directly address those weaknesses. Resources that feel slightly challenging but not overwhelming sit in the optimal learning zone that linguists call <strong>comprehensible input plus one</strong> — material that is just a step above your current ability.</p>

