  <h3>In-Depth App Reviews: What Each Tool Does Best</h3>

  <p><strong>Anki</strong> is not a Chinese app — it is a general-purpose spaced repetition flashcard system, and that is exactly what makes it powerful. Unlike apps that lock you into their curriculum, Anki lets you build or download custom decks tailored to your exact needs. The most popular shared decks for Chinese learners include full HSK vocabulary sets (HSK 1 through HSK 6), sentence-based decks that teach words in context, and audio decks with native speaker recordings. The learning curve is steeper than polished apps like Duolingo, but the payoff is dramatically better long-term retention. Set your daily new cards to 10-15 per day, review every morning, and you will steadily build a vocabulary of thousands of words within a year.</p>

  <p><strong>Pleco</strong> deserves special attention because it serves as the Swiss Army knife of Chinese learning. The free version alone includes a comprehensive dictionary with over 130,000 entries, example sentences, audio pronunciation, and radical-based character lookup. Power users benefit from the paid add-ons: the OCR camera lets you scan printed Chinese text in real time, the clipboard reader automatically looks up any Chinese text you copy on your phone, and the built-in flashcard system turns every word you look up into a review card. If you install only one paid add-on, choose the OCR camera — it transforms real-world Chinese text into an interactive learning experience.</p>

  <p><strong>HelloChinese</strong> stands out among structured course apps because it takes tones seriously from the very first lesson. Each lesson includes tone drills with speech recognition that will not let you advance until your pronunciation is reasonably accurate. The free tier covers a substantial portion of HSK 1 and HSK 2 material, making it an excellent zero-cost starting point. Where HelloChinese falls short is in its limited intermediate and advanced content — once you finish the beginner modules, you will need to transition to other resources.</p>

  <h3>Free vs. Paid: Where to Spend and Where to Save</h3>

  <p>You can reach conversational fluency in Chinese entirely with free resources, but a few strategic paid investments can save significant time. Here is how to think about it: free tools like Anki, Pleco's core dictionary, YouTube channels, and podcasts cover vocabulary, listening, and reference needs comprehensively. Where paid resources earn their value is in structured feedback and accountability. A monthly subscription to an app like Skritter (around $15/month) provides handwriting correction that no free tool matches. A few sessions with an online tutor on italki ($10-15 per hour for community tutors) gives you personalized speaking feedback that self-study cannot replicate. The most cost-effective strategy is to keep your daily tools free and allocate a small monthly budget — even $20-30 — toward one or two paid services that address your biggest weakness.</p>

