  <h3>Building a Study Stack by Level</h3>
  <p>Your ideal combination of tools should evolve as your level improves. Think of your resources as a stack that you rebuild every few months based on progress. At the <strong>beginner stage</strong>, your stack should be simple: HelloChinese or ChineseSkill for structured lessons, Anki for vocabulary retention, Pleco as your constant dictionary companion, and Coffee Break Chinese or Little Fox for gentle listening exposure. Keep the total to three or four tools and resist the urge to add more until you have used these consistently for at least one month.</p>

  <p>At the <strong>intermediate stage</strong>, swap out the beginner course app and replace it with input-heavy resources. Your stack might include Anki (continuing from beginner), Du Chinese or The Chairman's Bao for graded reading, Slow Chinese or Mandarin Corner for listening, and a weekly language exchange session on Tandem or HelloTalk for speaking practice. This is also the stage where native content starts becoming accessible — try following one or two Chinese social media accounts and reading their posts daily, even if you need to look up several words per post.</p>

  <p>At the <strong>advanced stage</strong>, your tools should shift almost entirely to native content consumption. Replace graded readers with real Chinese novels, news articles from sources like BBC Chinese or Caixin, and podcasts made for native speakers. Keep Anki for specialized vocabulary in your areas of interest — business terms, academic language, or literary expressions. At this stage, the most valuable investment is regular conversation with native speakers, whether through language exchange, online tutoring, or in-person interaction. Your goal is no longer to learn Chinese in isolation but to use Chinese as a medium for learning about other topics that interest you.</p>

